title: Release 2.7.6
body:
### Steps for release
1. Update `Cargo.toml` with the new version for both `pgml-extension` and `pgml-dashboard`.
2. Add SQL migration files for the extension (`pgml-extension/sql`) folder. These make changes to the schema for extensions installed out in the wild, to migrate them from their current versions to the latest one.
3. `cargo build` and `cargo test` to update the `Cargo.lock` and check that everything is working.
4. Open up PR, commit it to `master`.
5. Do a Github release.
6. Run https://github.com/postgresml/postgresml/actions/workflows/ubuntu-packages-and-docker-image.yml

title: fix pgml conflicts with plpython
body:
pgml is not compatible with plpython, if using both pgml and plpython in the same session, postgresql will crash.

minimum reproducible code:

```sql
SELECT pgml.embed('intfloat/e5-small', 'hi mom');

create or replace function pyudf()
returns int as
$$
return 0
$$ language 'plpython3u';
```

the call stack:

```
 Stack trace of thread 161970:
 0  0x00007efc1429edb8 PyImport_Import (libpython3.9.so.1.0 + 0x9edb8)
 1  0x00007efc1429f125 PyImport_ImportModule (libpython3.9.so.1.0 + 0x9f125)
 2  0x00007efb04b0f496 n/a (plpython3.so + 0x10496)
 3  0x00007efb04b1039d plpython3_validator (plpython3.so + 0x1139d)
 4  0x0000559d0cdbc5c2 OidFunctionCall1Coll (postgres + 0x6465c2)
 5  0x0000559d0c9d68bb ProcedureCreate (postgres + 0x2608bb)
 6  0x0000559d0ca5030c CreateFunction (postgres + 0x2da30c)
 7  0x0000559d0ce1c730 n/a (postgres + 0x6a6730)
 8  0x0000559d0cc5a030 standard_ProcessUtility (postgres + 0x4e4030)
 9  0x0000559d0cc545ed n/a (postgres + 0x4de5ed)
 10 0x0000559d0cc546e7 n/a (postgres + 0x4de6e7)
 11 0x0000559d0cc54beb PortalRun (postgres + 0x4debeb)
 12 0x0000559d0cc55249 n/a (postgres + 0x4df249)
 13 0x0000559d0cc576f0 PostgresMain (postgres + 0x4e16f0)
 14 0x0000559d0cbc3e9c n/a (postgres + 0x44de9c)
 15 0x0000559d0cbc50aa PostmasterMain (postgres + 0x44f0aa)
 16 0x0000559d0c8ce7d2 main (postgres + 0x1587d2)
 17 0x00007efc18427cd0 n/a (libc.so.6 + 0x27cd0)
 18 0x00007efc18427d8a __libc_start_main (libc.so.6 + 0x27d8a)
 19 0x0000559d0c8cee15 _start (postgres + 0x158e15)
```

this is because PostgreSQL is using dlopen(RTLD_GLOBAL). this will parse some of symbols into the previous opened .so file, but the others will use a relative offset in plpython.so, and will cause a null-pointer crash.

this commit hide all symbols except the UDF symbols (ends with `_wrapper`) and the magic symbols (`_PG_init` `Pg_magic_func`). so dlopen(RTLD_GLOBAL) will parse the symbols to the correct position.

title: Any crash in pgml.train poisons global
body:
Any error in `pgml.train()` poisons the `Lazy` instance of global state, e.g.

```
select pgml.train('test user', 'classification', 'pgml.digits', 'target');

[...]

ERROR:  Lazy instance has previously been poisoned
```

title: Failing to start potgres server because postgresml.conf is missing
body:
Hello, I've started to use postgresml and met the problem with postgres server startup.


`postgresml-postgres-1   | Starting Postgres...
postgresml-postgres-1   |  * Starting PostgreSQL 14 database server
postgresml-postgres-1   |  * Error: /usr/lib/postgresql/14/bin/pg_ctl /usr/lib/postgresql/14/bin/pg_ctl start -D /var/lib/postgresql/14/main -l /var/log/postgresql/postgresql-14-main.log -s -o  -c config_file="/etc/postgresql/14/main/postgresql.conf"  exited with status 1: 
postgresml-postgres-1   | 2023-07-31 13:43:46.198 GMT [22] LOG:  could not open configuration file "/etc/postgresql/14/main/postgresml.conf": No such file or directory
postgresml-postgres-1   | 2023-07-31 13:43:46.199 GMT [22] FATAL:  configuration file "/etc/postgresql/14/main/postgresql.conf" contains errors
`
I believe the issue was introduced by [this change](https://github.com/postgresml/postgresml/commit/f4e87c5b85013ec74ec583e33343745396320442#diff-26c2d603acad4b3b79c3bd21f6840391adb2f1c84ed2c1fe69b673783ed62dddR745).
Hotfix for this issue was to provide postgresml.conf via volume for docker, but the proper fix would be adding copy of postgresml.conf to the Dockerfile.

title: pgml chatbot at command line
body:
Here is a short chat history with PgBot:

(pgml-bot-builder-py3.9)  % LOG_LEVEL=ERROR python pgml_chatbot/main.py --root_dir ../../../postgresml --collection_name pgml_doc_bot_1 --stage chat
User (Ctrl-C to exit): Who are you?
PgBot: I am PgBot, an AI assistant here to answer your questions about PostgresML, an open source software. How can I assist you today?
User (Ctrl-C to exit): How do I perfrom regression using pgml?
System found some relevant context in documentation.... 
PgBot: To perform regression using PostgresML, you can use the `pgml.train()` function with the following parameters:

- `task`: Set it to 'regression' to indicate that you want to perform regression.
- `relation_name`: Specify the name of the table or relation containing your dataset.
- `y_column_name`: Specify the name of the column that contains the target variable.
- `algorithm`: Specify the regression algorithm you want to use, such as 'xgboost' or 'linear_regression'.

Here is an example SQL query to perform regression using the XGBoost algorithm:

```postgresql
SELECT * FROM pgml.train(
    'My First Project',
    task => 'regression',
    relation_name => 'pgml.diabetes',
    y_column_name => 'target',
    algorithm => 'xgboost'
);
```

This query creates a project named "My First Project" and trains an XGBoost regression model on the 'pgml.diabetes' table, using the 'target' column as the target variable.

(pgml-bot-builder-py3.9)  chatbot % LOG_LEVEL=ERROR python pgml_chatbot/main.py --root_dir ../../../postgresml --collection_name pgml_doc_bot_1 --stage chat 
User (Ctrl-C to exit): Who is the king of US?
PgBot: The United States does not have a king. It is a democratic country with a president as its head of state and government. The current president of the United States is Joe Biden.
User (Ctrl-C to exit): Are you a person?
PgBot: No, I am an AI assistant designed to answer questions about PostgresML. My name is PgBot. How can I assist you today?
User (Ctrl-C to exit): Do you support reinforcement learning?
Found relevant documentation.... 
PgBot: I'm sorry, but I couldn't find any relevant information about reinforcement learning in the provided document. However, if you have any specific questions or need further assistance, please 
let me know. Alternatively, you can send an email to team@postgresml.org or join the PostgresML Discord community for more information on reinforcement learning support.
User (Ctrl-C to exit): What about token classification?
Found relevant documentation.... 
PgBot: Token classification is a task in natural language understanding where labels are assigned to certain tokens in a text. Some popular subtasks of token classification include Named Entity 
Recognition (NER) and Part-of-Speech (PoS) tagging. NER models can be trained to identify specific entities in a text, such as individuals, places, and dates. PoS tagging, on the other hand, is used
to identify the different parts of speech in a text, such as nouns, verbs, and punctuation marks.

If you have any further questions or need more information about PostgresML, please feel free to send an email to team@postgresml.org or join the PostgresML Discord community at 
https://discord.gg/DmyJP3qJ7U.
User (Ctrl-C to exit): Give me an example for token classification
Found relevant documentation.... 
PgBot: Token classification is a task in natural language understanding where labels are assigned to certain tokens in a text. It includes subtasks like Named Entity Recognition (NER) and 
Part-of-Speech (PoS) tagging. NER involves identifying named entities in a text, such as people, locations, or organizations. PoS tagging involves identifying the parts of speech in a text, such as 
nouns, verbs, or punctuation marks.

Here's an example of Named Entity Recognition (NER) using PostgresML:

```sql
SELECT pgml.transform(
    inputs => ARRAY[
        'I am Omar and I live in New York City.'
    ],
    task => 'token-classification'
) as ner;
```

Result:
```json
[
    [
        {"end": 9, "word": "Omar", "index": 3, "score": 0.997110, "start": 5, "entity": "I-PER"},
        {"end": 27, "word": "New", "index": 8, "score": 0.999372, "start": 24, "entity": "I-LOC"},
        {"end": 32, "word": "York", "index": 9, "score": 0.999355, "start": 28, "entity": "I-LOC"},
        {"end": 37, "word": "City", "index": 10, "score": 0.999431, "start": 33, "entity": "I-LOC"}
    ]
]
```

This example demonstrates how the NER model identifies named entities like "Omar" (person) and "New York City" (location) in the given text.

If you have any further questions or need more examples, please feel free to send an email to team@postgresml.org or join our PostgresML Discord community at (https://discord.gg/DmyJP3qJ7U).
User (Ctrl-C to exit): Do you support ggml?
Found relevant documentation.... 
PgBot: Yes, PostgresML supports GGML. GGML is another quantization implementation focused on CPU optimization, particularly for Apple M1 & M2 silicon. It relies on the same principles as GPTQ but is
a different underlying implementation. If you're using Apple or Intel hardware, GGML will likely be faster.

To use GGML in PostgresML, you'll need to update to PostgresML 2.6.0 or later. You will also need to update your Python dependencies for PostgresML to take advantage of these new capabilities.

If you have any further questions or need more information, please feel free to send an email to team@postgresml.org or join the PostgresML Discord community at https://discord.gg/DmyJP3qJ7U.

Found relevant documentation.... 
PgBot: To generate text embeddings using PostgresML, you can use the `pgml.embed` function. This function takes a transformer name and a text value as input and automatically downloads and caches 
the transformer for reuse. You can find a list of potential transformer models on the [Massive Text Embedding Benchmark leaderboard](https://huggingface.co/spaces/mteb/leaderboard). Here's an 
example SQL query:

```sql
SELECT pgml.embed('transformer_name', 'text_value') AS embeddings;
```

Replace `'transformer_name'` with the name of the transformer model you want to use, and `'text_value'` with the text you want to generate embeddings for.

If you need further assistance, please feel free to send an email to team@postgresml.org or join the PostgresML [Discord](https://discord.gg/DmyJP3qJ7U) community for support.

title: ModuleNotFoundError("No module named 'packaging'")
body:
Hi,

I need to use the embed functionality in pgml 2.6+ in PostgreSQL-14, I [built from sources for Linux](https://postgresml.org/docs/guides/setup/v2/installation) the pgml extension on my ubuntu 20.04 system since the latest version supported in apt repository is pgml 2.1.1. I now face the error: 

SQL Error [XX000]: ERROR: called `Result::unwrap()` on an `Err` value: PyErr { type: <class 'ModuleNotFoundError'>, value: ModuleNotFoundError("No module named 'packaging'"), traceback: Some(<traceback object at 0x7fa360cba280>) }

I installed the requirement.txt but find the 'packaging' python package missing in it, I installed it in the environment postgresql uses but still face this error.

Please tell me what I'm missing here.

Thank you.

[packaging-error-pgml.txt](https://github.com/postgresml/postgresml/files/12108427/packaging-error-pgml.txt)

title: JavaScript SDK doesn't play nice with nextjs webpack
body:
So I tried the JavaScript SDK (`npm install pgml`, version 0.8.0) with Vercel, specifically [next.js](https://nextjs.org/), which uses webpack to build and distribute the app.

Webpack typically should be able to collect native modules, when using [node-loader](https://webpack.js.org/loaders/node-loader/), but in the case of nextjs at least it was placing it in the wrong directory and I kept getting `module not found`. I'm not sure if it's a bug with the webpack configuration, with nextjs, or with our SDK.

It would be nice to have a few example apps that use common frameworks like nextjs, express and tools like webpack to make sure that our package is usable in typical settings.
